                                    <h2>Setup</h2>
                                </div>
                                <div class="clearfix">
                                    <p>First you need to include the jQuery library, since ClassyBox is a plugin. You can download it from the <a href="http://www.jquery.com">jQuery website</a> or link it directly from the Google CDN.</p>
                                    <pre>&lt;script src="https://ajax.googleapis.com/ajax/libs/jquery/1.10.2/jquery.min.js"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;</pre>
                                    <p>Secondly, you need to include the jQuery ClassyBox javascript, the css file and the required JWPlayer dependencies into your page. You can do it by adding the code below to your page.</p>
                                    <pre>&lt;script src="js/jquery.classybox.min.js"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;script src="js/jwplayer.js"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;script src="js/jwplayer.html5.js"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="css/jquery.classybox.min.css" /&gt;</pre>
                                    <p>Next, you implement the structure on which you want to trigger the classybox.</p>
                                    <pre>&lt;a class="lightbox" href="images/demo/1.jpg" title="First Image"&gt;
    &lt;img src="images/demo/1_tb.jpg" alt="This is a longer description" /&gt;
&lt;/a&gt;</pre>
                                    <p>As the last step, you trigger the <em>ClassyBox()</em> function on the element you just created. In this case, we trigger it on the element with the class <em>lightbox</em>. We can also use the old LightBox-compatible syntax, so you don't need to alter your website code.</p>
                                    <pre>$('.lightbox').ClassyBox({
    width: 900
});

$('a[rel^=lightbox]'.ClassyBox({
    width: 900
});</pre>
